<section xml:id="lesson2_1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Using the Circuit Builder to Learn Gates </title>

  <p>
    The circuit builder allows us to learn about the behavior of a simple gate by trying
    all of the combinations of inputs. We will use the circuit builder to discover the
    functionality of a new gate, the <c>SWAP</c> gate, which operates on two qubits, but first
    we will learn how to create multi-qubit gates by connecting gate tiles.
  </p>

  <section xml:id="sec-building-2-qubit-gates">
    <title>Creating a <c>SWAP</c> Gate</title>

    <sidebyside widths="75% 25%" valign="middle">
      <p>
        Use the circuit builder below to make a <c>SWAP</c> gate.
        To create a <c>SWAP</c> gate, you will need to:
      <ol>
        <li>Drag two <em>Swap</em> gate tiles onto the circuit, aligning them vertically.</li>
        <li>Click the number at the top of the column to select them as a group.</li>
        <li>Click the "C/S" button to connect the tiles.</li>
      </ol>
      When you are finished, you should see a line connecting the two tiles,
      indicating that you have created a <c>SWAP</c> gate.
      </p>
      <image source="L2.1_SWAP.png" width="40%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <interactive aspect="9:9" platform="javascript"
      source="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/dmfranklin/quantum-module/source/loader.js">
      <script>
        identicalCircuitWidget({
          circuit: "L2_1_0",
          instantFeedback: true,
          allowedGates: "S"
        });
      </script>
    </interactive>

  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-exploring-SWAP">
    <title>Exploring the <c>SWAP</c> Gate</title>
    <p>
      Given two qubits in their simplest states, <m>\ket{0}</m> and <m>\ket{1}</m>,
      there are four combinations of inputs and four combinations of outputs:
      <m>\ket{00}</m>, <m>\ket{01}</m>, <m>\ket{10}</m>, and <m>\ket{11}</m>.
      To see how a gate works on these simple states, we can try each in the circuit builder.
    </p>
    <p>
      Notice the compact form that can be used to describe these states.
      Qubits shown top-to-bottom in a circuit are expressed left-to-right.
      That is, the state <m>\ket{01}</m> means the top qubit is <m>\ket{0}</m> and
      the bottom qubit is <m>\ket{1}</m>.
    </p>

    <sidebyside widths="75% 25%" valign="top">
      <p>
        Now, let's see how the <c>SWAP</c> gate acts when given the input <m>\ket{00}</m>.
        The circuit builder will be set to a starting state of <m>\ket{0}</m> and <m>\ket{0}</m>,
        or <m>\ket{00}</m> in the compact form. Use the circuit builder to create a circuit that
        matches the one pictured on the right.
      </p>
      <image source="Swap00.png" width="66%" />
    </sidebyside>

    <interactive aspect="9:9" platform="javascript"
      source="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/dmfranklin/quantum-module/source/loader.js">
      <script>
        visualizeProbabilitiesWidget({
          circuit: "Blank 2x6",
          allowedGates: "S"
        });
      </script>
    </interactive>

    <p>
      Notice that there is a bar graph that shows the probability of each outcome. Because
      we are using a simple state, there will be a 100% probability of one of the four
      choices of outcomes.
    </p>

    <exercise label="Swap_00_Output">
      <title>Record output for <c>SWAP</c> with <m>\ket{00}</m>
      </title>
      <idx>swap output 00</idx>
      <statement>
        <p>What was the output of your <c>SWAP</c> gate with an input of: <m>\ket{00}</m> or <m>\ket{⚪⚪}</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="no">
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{00}</m> or <m>\ket{⚪⚪}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Yes! That is correct. The <c>SWAP</c> had no effect!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{01}</m> or <m>\ket{⚪⚫}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you hooked up your circuit correctly!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{10}</m> or <m>\ket{⚫⚪}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you hooked up your circuit correctly!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>

        <choice>
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\ket{11}</m> or <m>\ket{⚫⚫}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>Make sure you hooked up your circuit correctly!</p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
      <hint>
        <p>Make the circuit and look at the bar graph below the circuit.
          The answer is the choice on the bar graph at 100%.</p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>

    <p>
      Now, we are going to try vary the input to the circuit.
      Let's see how the <c>SWAP</c> gate acts when given the input <m>\ket{01}</m>.
      To change the input from <m>\ket{00}</m> to <m>\ket{01}</m>,
      you will place a <c>NOT</c> gate on the bottom qubit before the <c>SWAP</c> gate in the circuit.
    </p>

